<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Poguk</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Teacher<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jun 2002<br />
	Location: Columbus, IN
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>If you can summon a persistent pet, you are a pet class.<br />
<br />
Where do you guys get this stuff: "SOE doesn't consider us a pet class."  Where do you get that?  I've been playing this game for over 4 years and I've never read anything like that.  Never ONCE did I read an SOE publication that said "Mages/necros/bsts are pet classes; shamans and SKs are NOT."  Someone's making up some fluff!<br />
<br />
"Companions"?  That's your technical reason why shaman are not a pet class?  Well, necros have "minions".  They don't cast a spell called "Summon Pet."  So I guess technically necros aren't a pet class either.  Pffft!<br />
<br />
I'll re-iterate it: If you can summon a persistent pet, you are a pet class.<br />
<br />
When you have pet spells well into your upper levels, and they summon creatures that are within 7 levels of your own level, with 3k hps and quads for 60 (alpha'd and buffed) and does around 40 DPS, and enrages, THAT'S a pet.  Sorry to say it.  Just because they aren't quite as strong as mage/necro/bst pets, doesn't mean they don't qualify.  Dogdog parses out to 35-40 DPS consistently.  The mage and bst pets that commonly get stuck in my parses do roughly 65 DPS, which is hardly earth-shattering.  Not compared to rogues, monks, rangers, wizards who pump out 100-150 DPS in their sleep.  Occasionally I'll see a warder go ballistic and approach 80 DPS.  Woo!  The owner of that pet has a minimum of 300 AAs and full LDoN pet augs.<br />
<br />
Remember the 49 necro pet?  Used to be the beast of EQ?  That's now the final SK pet.  He does about 40-45 DPS if fully buffed.  THAT's a pet.  Combined with a good SK who can get around 100 DPS just by himself, and you have a owner/pet combo approaching 140-150 DPS in their sleep.  I see it all the time...  The SK pet is NOT insignificant in most situations, especially xp/ldon groups.  In a lot of situations, I've found the only reason the SK doesn't summon one is because they just plain are lazy.  Their preference, but that's not something to ignore.  Just like the occasional shaman you find who doesn't bother with pets because they don't find them to be worth it.  Rubbish!<br />
<br />
If I'm a shaman, and I have a chance to add an element to my group that does 40 DPS and makes mobs fall that much faster, I summon the damn pet.  It's something I always have up and rely on in groups... I always have a pet by my side 'cept for raids, and therefore I'm by all means a "pet-class".<br />
<br />
And yes, I'd like an aug for dogdog.</p>
	
	
	
